data.content:
Here's a complete migration analysis and replacement for your code.

## Inventory of Thread.Abort usage

| Location | API | Pattern |
|---|---|---|
| `Stop()` | `_workerThread.Abort()` | Cancellable work loop |
| `ProcessLoop()` | `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Control flow for cleanup |
| `ProcessLoop()` | `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Continue execution after abort |
| `ProcessLoop()` | `GetNextItem()` blocks | Blocking call interruption |

All three APIs (`Thread.Abort`, `ThreadAbortException`, `Thread.ResetAbort`) throw `PlatformNotSupportedException` or are meaningless in .NET 8.

## Migrated code

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private Thread? _workerThread;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        var token = _cts.Token;
        _workerThread = new Thread(() => ProcessLoop(token));
        _workerThread.IsBackground = true;
        _workerThread.Start();
    }

    private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                var item = GetNextItem(token); // pass token to unblock
                ProcessItem(item);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Cancellation requested — clean up partial work
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                break; // exit the loop (replaces ResetAbort + loop re-check)
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        if (_cts is null || _workerThread is null)
            return;

        _cts.Cancel(); // signals the token — cooperative, not forced

        // Wait for the thread to finish gracefully
        if (!_workerThread.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2)))
        {
            // Thread didn't stop in time. Log a warning — you cannot
            // force-kill it in modern .NET. See pitfalls below.
        }
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts?.Dispose();
        _cts = null;
    }
}
```

## Key changes explained

| .NET Framework | .NET 8 | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `volatile bool _running` | `CancellationTokenSource` + `CancellationToken` | Token can interrupt blocking calls; a bool cannot |
| `Thread.Abort()` | `_cts.Cancel()` | Cooperative signal instead of forced exception injection |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)` | The `when` guard avoids catching unrelated OCEs |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | `break` | You control the loop — just exit it |
| `Thread.Sleep(2000)` | `_workerThread.Join(2000)` | Actually waits for the thread instead of hoping |
| (none) | `IDisposable` | `CancellationTokenSource` leaks timers if not disposed |

## Critical: `GetNextItem` must cooperate

The **biggest pitfall** — if `GetNextItem()` blocks (e.g., on a `BlockingCollection`, socket, or `WaitHandle`), cancellation won't work unless you thread the token through:

```csharp
// BEFORE — blocks indefinitely, immune to cancellation
private Item GetNextItem()
{
    return _queue.Take(); // no way to wake this up
}

// AFTER — unblocks when token is cancelled
private Item GetNextItem(CancellationToken token)
{
    return _queue.Take(token); // throws OperationCanceledException
}
```

If you're using a `ManualResetEvent` or similar:
```csharp
// Replace event.WaitOne() with:
WaitHandle.WaitAny(new[] { event, token.WaitHandle });
token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();
```

## Common pitfalls for this migration

1. **"Thread didn't stop" — no fallback.** Unlike Framework, there is no `Thread.Abort()` fallback. If `GetNextItem` blocks without accepting a token, the thread hangs forever. You **must** make blocking calls cancellation-aware.

2. **Long-running `ProcessItem` needs checkpoints.** If `ProcessItem` takes minutes, add `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` at safe points inside it — cancellation only fires at checkpoints.

3. **Don't swallow `OperationCanceledException`.** Only catch it at the top-level loop. If inner methods catch and suppress it, cancellation silently fails.

4. **Dispose the `CancellationTokenSource`.** It allocates timers and callbacks internally. Leaking it is a real resource leak, hence the `IDisposable` pattern above.

5. **Uncooperative third-party code.** If `GetNextItem` calls a library you can't modify and it blocks forever, the only escape hatch is to move that work to a **separate process** and use `Process.Kill()`.
